# Code Quality Standards

## TypeScript
- Strict mode enabled — no `any` types
- Define interfaces for all data shapes (Suburb, Service, BlogPost, Page)
- Use `satisfies` for type checking object literals
- Export types from `types/` directory

## No Hardcoded Strings
- No hardcoded phone numbers — use `SITE_CONFIG.phone`
- No hardcoded emails — use `SITE_CONFIG.email`
- No hardcoded addresses — use `SITE_CONFIG.address`
- No hardcoded business name — use `SITE_CONFIG.name`
- All config in `lib/constants.ts`

```typescript
// lib/constants.ts
export const SITE_CONFIG = {
  name: 'Zap It Pest & Termite Control Melbourne',
  phone: '03 9126 0555',
  phoneTel: 'tel:0391260555',
  email: 'info@zapitpestmelbourne.com.au',
  address: '80 Porter Rd, Heidelberg Heights, VIC 3081',
  url: 'https://zapitpestmelbourne.com.au',
} as const;
```

## Security
- Never expose Supabase service key in client code
- Use `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix only for truly public env vars
- Sanitize all user inputs (contact form, search)
- Use Supabase RLS for all tables
- No `eval()`, no `innerHTML` except for JSON-LD schema

## Error Handling
- Every async function must have try/catch
- Use error.tsx boundary for route segments
- Log errors with context, never swallow silently
- Return user-friendly fallback UI on error

## Component Patterns
- One component per file
- Props interface defined above component
- Destructure props in function signature
- Use `cn()` from `lib/utils` for conditional classes
- Prefer composition over prop drilling
